4.25/5  rDev -3.4%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Bottle from Binny's in Schaumburg, IL
No bottled on date noticed
Poured into a standard US pint glass
Dark tan to light brown head fades over a minute or two to a thick ring around the glass with some sparse, thin islands of foam capping the top of the body. The fading head leaves spotty lacing, which is renewed or modified with each sip. Body is black or very, very dark brown. Even when held directly to a light, only the barest trace of brown can be made out along the outline of the body. Impossible to see through, but the ring of foam persists throughout, so there must be some constantly percolating upwards.
Primary aromas of coffee grounds, chocolate syrup, roasted malt, and a mild sweetness (more notable as the beer warms). Can also smell a bit of ethanol.
The taste opens with roasted malt sweetness and mild char on the front of the tongue. Mid-palate brings forward an intense coffee surge, combined with notable chocolate and roasted malt flavors. I also get some general spiciness, perhaps a bit of cumin, which is probably due to yeast byproducts and the ethanol in the beer. The taste is generally very well-mixed with an emphasis on coffee that does not outstrip the other elements of the beer. Back of the palate bring in continued coffee and chocolate flavors, but ethanol also becomes apparent. Going down, I'm reminded of a dense coffee brownie with a small chaser of vodka. Aftertaste is of coffee, coffee-like bitterness, and perhaps some dark chocolate.
Body is medium-heavy to heavy, with strong enough carbonation to make this thick beer foam up slightly on the palate. The result is a fairly smooth, pillowy mouthfeel. Ethanol warmth is obvious from the beginning in the nostrils, and it can be felt burning the tongue and back of the throat as well; this is to be expected from a 9.5% ABV imperial stout. Finish is quite dry. 1,862 charactersfalloutsnow, Mar 08, 2012
