4.3/5  rDev -2.3%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5Peche Mortel, 32-oz growler fill from a firkin/cask at Whole Foods Bowery, part of their new and exciting "Firkin Fridays". 
Appearance: Served in my Sierra snifter, Peche Mortel pours outrageously black and flat, with barely a rim of bubbles and a whitish mantle for a head. Looks very flat and still, opaque and dark, not unlike day-old coffee. Temperature is warm, perfectly cask-y and "natural".
Smell: Sharp booze, gasoline, temperature rising. Some wood, fire, flotsam and jetsam on a remote beach. Coffee. Chocolate, cake. Bourbon! A tad of barnyard, open air and wet fields.
Taste: This is like drinking chocolate milk or cold coffee, plus brown sugar and some creme brulee or dark-chocolate pudding. There is a freshly-ground coffee-bean taste at the end of the sip that is just unique. Roasty, bitter, nice! But very well played, though. This is not like Founders Breakfast Stout, where I felt like the coffee was overtly bitter and not pleasant. Peche Mortel is pretty much all coffee, but nicely done. Also, some whipped-cream, as in a topping for a Starbucks coffee (but better, if you know what I mean). Sugar, fire-booze at the very end. Tongue- and lip-smacking!
Mouthfeel: Perfect cask! Absolutely no carbonation, medium-to-full body and full flavor. Boozy-hot as it goes down, warms the throat and the esophagus nicely. Chewy and big and boozy, this is not a beer to be taken lightly. Hot but cool.
Overall: I was *this* close to finish a 32-oz growler in one quick sitting. I love this beer! Drinks so well, despite being boozy. Beautiful taste and everything else. Had it before on cask at a bar (d.b.a. in Brooklyn) and out of a bottle; firkin growler is my favorite serving, then bar cask. 1,716 charactersDoubleSimcoe, Jun 25, 2011
